@Peeper: Right. It's definitely your idea. However, you didn't code it. Ideas =/= credit. I closed a lot of your features because they're not at all what I had in mind for Kaffiene. You're free to fork my code and make it yourself.

If we're going with 'ideas', then I have to give most of the credit to the guy who make ZeroSearch. I literally cloned his site, engine, index, etc. and just built on it and improved the usability. I'm fairly open about credit. I coded the ZeroWiki info box, but ofc. I didn't come up with that idea on my own. Just like many of the features in Kaffiene. I simply implemented them after they were suggested. However, I don't claim to have made things that I took. The index format? That wasn't me at all (except the addition of siterank).

@Jayofthezero: It previously used an XMLHttpRequest to fetch the .db file from ZeroWiki, and then searched through it. However, now it uses the new remote fileget and cors permission to fetch the file. You can check it out on the [Github](https://github.com/April93/Kaffiene/blob/master/index.html#L25). Or just looking at the first few lines of index.html in the kaffiene folder.

There's a lot of parsing and formatting to make the results good. You can find that in the [fetchfromdb()](https://github.com/April93/Kaffiene/blob/master/index.html#L134) function. Located a bit later down.

@空澄砂夜: Hey, absolutely no worries about that. ZeroNet is meant for everyone, not just english speakers. It's a little frustrating to not understand most of the content, but that's on me. Usually I just skip over the stuff I can't read, but I saw Kaffiene mentioned, and poked my head in. Looks like some cool stuff so I wanted to say hey.

All you chinese guys are absolutely inspiring. I love seeing people use ZeroNet in a way that's only really talked about in hypotheticals here in the US. More people is more people. Even if some people only speak chinese (I'm sure there's probably plenty), they'll bring in other people, and we'll eventually get a huge community of a variety of languages.

I'm actually a bit sad about the language barrier. It happens a lot unfortunately, and not just here. I'd love to interact with the chinese community here a bit more. Maybe I should start learning chinese haha. At the moment I just use google translate to try and get the gist of things, and have my BF translate some stuff.

>Do I need to worry about two people having the same zeroid? 

ZeroIDs, no. Usernames, yes. There's no guarantee usernames will be unique on services like KaffieID or other ID providers. ZeroID, however, guarantees uniqueness. The proper thing to do is to use the auth_address, which is always guaranteed to be unique.

@nofish: Yet again I'm gonna complain about ZN's heavy reliance on the assumption of unique names. IIRC, the banlist still assumes usernames are unique. Also: certs should have the signer public key attached to them, and there should be an "allow all" for signer permissions.

@Ivesen: Both twitter and emojione have licenses available for public use. The original docomo and softbank are available on their company websites (no idea about licenses), several are publicly available fonts (Unifont, Symbola, Quivira). Mozilla's is prolly pretty open. There's one I downloaded off github that has a fairly open license.

The rest.... yeah are not exactly being open/libre/free/whatever. But somehow I really doubt they care unless you're making money off it.

That's actually what got me going on about this, tbh. Letting people have freedom over what emoji font they use. And perhaps going about making a new one as well.
